Title: This is how to love.
Description:
What is love?  and How do I know?  Where can I learn...  What is my love?  What is God's Love, and what's the difference?  Inspired by the many implications of Jesus' commandment to love one another.  What is love?  And how do I know.  

PLEASE HELP!! üôè Consider supporting us: https://www.imbeggar.com/take-action

https://www.facebook.com/IMbeggar


Video Transcript:

I love I you.

now before you laugh or make fun of me, or just think I'm weird,

let me tell you what I mean by that first.

I don‚Äôt mean it in some fake, warm and fuzzy, sentimental kind of way. 

And I‚Äôm not saying it just to be nice, or to look good, or to get you to like me. 

What I mean is, at the very least, I only want what is good for you. 

At the very most, I mean, i'll give myself, my life, in any way I can, for your good.

And I don‚Äôt care how I feel, or how I look, or what Im getting out of it, 

or if I feel like it or not.

Love doesn't go this way.  

Only this way. 

And who are you?

Well you could be anyone.

my friend, my family, my spouse, person I like. 

well thats easy, anyone can love the people they like.   

What about the person I don't like, the person who doesn't like me, the person nobody likes,

what about the person I totally disagree with, the person who's completely different from me, there person I want to hate, the person everyone hates, the person who repulses me.

DOESN'T matter.

Love doesn't pick and choose who to love, just like the sun doesn‚Äôt pick and choose who to shine on, it just shines.

And what is your good?

Well it's all those little things that are gonna help us find the one thing that we all want, that we‚Äôre all searching for, 

happiness.

as much as we can find here in this life, but more importantly, the full happiness that we can only find in the next life.

and I'll love you no matter what you do, 

but that doesn't mean I‚Äôm going to love everything you do. 

Love has to be tough, sometimes even fierce.

If you do anything that's gonna harm, impede, poison, delay or divert your good, 

or the good of anyone else's, 

I have to stand against it, not you.

Even if it's awkward, even if it's unpopular, even if it's gonna turn you against me, 

for a little while. 

But even when love is tough,  

Love is always patient. 

That's why we have a whole lifetime. 

love is always gentle, kind, tender, loving, 

never pushy, preachy, pointing fingers, rigid or mean.

and I don‚Äôt care what you‚Äôve done, or how big you've screwed up, or how vast our differences are, or if your life is a giant, global sized disaster.  

love is bigger than all these things.  

And I don't care how worthless, or flawed, or unlovable, or insignificant, you think you may be.  

love breaks through all these.  

and if you get hurt, which we do, 

or get into trouble, which we do, 

or get beat up by the world, which we will.  

and you're tired, and angry, and bitter, and miserable, and scared, LIKE THE REST OF US, 

and feel like you‚Äôre, drifting all alone in a sea of, suffering‚Ä¶ 

ill suffer with you.  

and if we disagree and get into those epic fights, which we will, 

and even if you betray me, and laugh at me, and make me look stupid, 

and walk away a thousand times,

Ill forgive you, a million times,

because nothing that could ever happen in this tiny little universe, 

could ever be more important to me than you.  

Not even myself.  

This is what I mean when I say I love you‚Ä¶

but this is not my love‚Ä¶

my love is weak, and self-centered at best.  

this is his love.  

and he said, he commanded, 

go out there and love one another as I loved you.

so I'll say it say again even though I know i'm gonna fail at it a million times today.  

[I love you]

Title: LOVE is beautifully ORDINARY
Description:
Support us in creating more films like this : http://www.patreon.com/reflectionsoflife 
Thank you Justine & Michael üíö

Back in December 2022, we released a film featuring Antony and Margie, who shared with us some of their views on love and relationships. If you haven't seen this first film, you can watch it here - https://youtu.be/pbyQhbZJhwI

Following the overwhelming response to our initial video, we've received many messages asking for further glimpses into the lives of this fabulous couple. Your voices have been heard, and so we recently visited with them again. During our latest encounter, Antony and Margie chat more about the various stages of married life, and some of their secrets to a successful marriage. Their reflections are sure to resonate deeply with those of you who are seeking guidance on matters of the heart.

‚ÄúAn outstanding love doesn‚Äôt come from two half-fulfilled people coming together to make one whole, complete life. Outstanding love comes from two whole people coming together to share and enhance their already full and beautiful lives.‚Äù ~Pia Scade

Filmed in Colesburg, South Africa. 
Featuring Antony and Margie Osler (https://www.stoepzen.co.za/accommodation.html)

All of our films are made possible through the generous support of our patrons.
To be part of this journey : http://www.patreon.com/reflectionsoflife
If you'd prefer to make once off contribution, our PayPal details are : paypal.me/reflectionsfilms

Join our YouTube channel to get early access to our films :
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCcPPUszZ4-7yzZNgAAYwJjg/join

Who is Reflections of Life?  We are Justine and Michael (previously known as Green Renaissance).  We use our passion for filmmaking and our love of storytelling, to remind our audience of one simple truth ‚Äì that we are all human.  The more that we understand and believe in this interconnectedness, the more we will treat ourselves, one another, and planet earth with a greater sense of compassion.

In collaboration with iNous, we recently released a beautiful deck of 52 cards - each card containing a quote from one of our films, paired with the activating visual muses of Lanon Prigge.  The aim of this deck is to rekindle child-like curiosity and creativity, helping to navigate the shared waters of our human experience with grace and joy.  If you‚Äôd like to consider purchasing your copy, shop here - https://tgc.link/reflections

You can also sign up to take part in the Reflections of Life Intentional Journey, receiving a digital copy of each card direct to your email, over a consecutive 52 day period - https://www.inous.org/reflections-of-life-intentional-email-journey/

Caption Text: Well, what is love? What is love Antony?  What is love? This is about as good as it gets. And it seems to get better as we get older. But there will probably be a tipping point where we don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs going to happen and we‚Äôll just have to be willing to slide together down some slippery slope. When we got married we worked out a series of vows which we wrote out and we said to each other. I can‚Äôt really remember what they were except that it was something like that we hope one day we will sit here in our old age still together and just enjoy this life that we‚Äôve been given. Maybe we do need to renew our vows so that we remember what we said. But the one that stands out quite strongly which I feel we‚Äôre embodying now is, ‚ÄòMay our home be a place where people can accept themselves.‚Äô Which, when we drew that up, was a beautiful intention and I feel like we‚Äôre really living that. The other was that we don‚Äôt hide behind each other. That we have our own identity and are at one with ourselves. That we‚Äôre not hiding behind another person or expecting them to fulfil what is important to us. What is often hard to accept when you live so much inside yourself is that the person in front of you is very different to you. I think in a marriage that‚Äôs the hardest thing... to realise that some of the differences that you fell in love with in the beginning are the things that bug you later. I‚Äôve seen that in myself and with others. So those are the little daily things that need to be communicated and sat down and made a compromise.  I see that if I leave the butter out after I make toast that my wife is furious... daily. Then I think the one way I can show a commitment to the relationship is to either not have toast at all, or to have toast without butter, or to put the butter away. And I don‚Äôt have to talk to her about it, I don‚Äôt have to be analytical about it, you know, one picks it up. And of course there are things I do that will infuriate her  that I don‚Äôt pick up. She‚Äôll tell me... she‚Äôs not scared of me in that way. If I look back, there are stages in a married life. There‚Äôs the initial excitement of being together. And then of course the utter astonishment of having children. That was just wonderful, beyond measure. Sometimes it was really hard work. We had to earn a living. I had to travel to work. There were times we had to be apart, times we came together. And we didn‚Äôt resist it or complain... we just did it. And in retrospect that doing of it was a wonderful cementing of the relationship. Since then I‚Äôve stopped travelling. We spend all our time together now, pretty much. We sleep together, we eat together, we drink together. And it‚Äôs wonderful and there‚Äôs a whole new adjustment that happens. And I think that‚Äôs really precious. People talk about it‚Äôs difficult when your children leave home... of course our children have left home long ago... but for us it‚Äôs been wonderful. We‚Äôve had time on our own and we make as much use of it as we can. I think it‚Äôs very important to find something when your children leave home, that the two of you do together that is meaningful and nourishing to both of you. When I look around at my family and my friends, that‚Äôs often when couples go different ways. Then one feels that you‚Äôre living two separate lives. And it‚Äôs very difficult to find a place of connection because your priorities have been work, or children, or both. And now none of those are something that you share anymore. I never give advice... I wouldn‚Äôt take it anyway. But for us, what‚Äôs really helped was having, as Margie says, not only a common direction in our life but a sense that we actually deliberately do things together that are meaningful to us. Every night we gather around sunset and we watch the sun go down. In a sense, ritual in that way was always a part of our life. So we always have watched the sun go down. It was always important for us. And when the children were younger they would join us. And now that they‚Äôre not here we sit together and we talk about them all the time. Not all the time darling. But it‚Äôs quite a deliberate, ritualised part of the day. So we make it precious, I think that‚Äôs what we try and do. And it does become precious. Not so much because we set out to make something precious but we decided how we wanted to spend that time together. And it turned out to be precious, which is wonderful. I feel quite strongly, growing older, that however much I look back to a more romantic postcard version of what life could be that something fantastically, wonderfully ordinary has taken its place. Ordinary is extraordinary. If you think of your life, it‚Äôs the little things, the ordinary little things, that are very meaningful and you don‚Äôt forget them. Little kindnesses, little actions  that you don‚Äôt expect to happen, are the ordinary. And I think one of the most ordinary things that we humans are made to do is to be present and listen to each other. And I think it‚Äôs only when we stop that we see the extraordinary in the ordinary, when we really stop and feel and hear. In the same way that the leaves change in spring and fall in autumn and that certain birds appear at certain times of the year and the sun comes and the wind goes... all of that is part of my life. And she is absolutely, intimately as much a part of it as all of that. I live in the veld (nature) and my wife. That‚Äôs how it feels. I‚Äôm so pleased you live in me. I‚Äôd like to think that she feels something of the same. There‚Äôs a sense of almost the inevitability of looking around and finding you here next to me in the same way that I lift the blind in the morning  and see the sun come up. That has been a discovery for me that I did not anticipate. And I wish it for everybody. And I think if one gives oneself a chance it will appear all by itself. If I look over one day and she‚Äôs not there, it will be heartbreaking. That‚Äôs absolutely true. I will then as best I can honour the life that we‚Äôve had together. She is my life and my life will continue. Saying ‚Äòshe is my life‚Äô doesn‚Äôt mean that I have no life without her. Saying ‚Äòshe is my life‚Äô means that when she‚Äôs with me, it‚Äôs full of her. It means that when she dies and I‚Äôm still around that my life will consist of whatever there is around me. And that almost my duty to her would be to live that life as best as I can. As she mentioned, we undertook not to hide behind each other, that I only live through you. I live through you, but that‚Äôs just the beginning, it‚Äôs not the end. So that when you die I‚Äôll weep, I‚Äôll build you a fantastic grave overlooking the hills, and we‚Äôll have sirens and choirs of angels all over the place. And then I‚Äôll play music with the angels. That‚Äôs how it feels to me. And I‚Äôm not looking forward to it. It sounds like you are... the choir of angels. Shall I bring them on now? I think the way I would honour her would be to get on with the life that is left for me. That‚Äôs what she would wish for me, more than anything. She would want me to see the sun come up, to dig in the garden, to look after visitors, to make the bed properly at last. But I think that she would trust me that however sad it was that sadness would become my life and would be manure for whatever last days are left which are probably not going to be very many. But that would be a huge event for me. I‚Äôve got a little poem that I‚Äôd like to recite if I may? I‚Äôll try and remember it. I shaved my head for the children of Palestine. I swept up the leaves in the Jewish cemetery. My wife wrapped presents for the old ladies in the frail care home. My daughter washed the dishes after lunch. The Buddha of Compassion has 84 000 hands. Which of those are yours?

Title: A Homeless Girl‚Äôs Love Made Me Rich | @LoveBusterShow
Description:
Are you afraid of falling in love?¬†

Christian noticed someone hiding under a table at a restaurant. He peaked beneath the tablecloth to see a girl curled up in there. At this moment, his fiance showed up. She asked him what he was doing, and before he could answer, the mysterious girl kissed him. He pushed her away and got up: ‚ÄúI was looking for this‚Äù, Chris said while showing his fiance a gorgeous wedding ring. The woman smiled: ‚ÄúI would say yes if you weren‚Äôt hiding a mistress under this table‚Äù. She walked away, and Chris was left alone and confused. He turned to the girl and asked: ‚ÄúWhy did you do that? She loved me‚Äù. The girl was creepily calm: ‚ÄúThen why did she steal your ring?‚Äù.
Chris looked inside the velvet box and realized the jewel was indeed gone. 

He rushed after his fiance‚Ä¶ and saw her at a pawn shop, selling the ring. Chris was heartbroken. He collapsed on the floor, weakened by the pain. But the mysterious girl showed up once more: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm sorry. It‚Äôs all my fault. And I‚Äôm going to fix it‚Äù.

Title: How to love and be loved | Billy Ward | TEDxFoggyBottom
Description:
Through a story of one of his students, Billy shows the importance of loving others and of being loved. 

Billy Ward is a Licensed Professional Counselor (LPC) and has been practicing in for the past 13 years in the New York City Suburbs of New Jersey. In addition to having a private practice, he has also been counseling students at Seton Hall Prep High School since 1998.  Currently he is the director of retreats for the school and also teaches a senior course for Human Development and Theology. Billy's approach to teaching centers on the development of mind, body and spirit. His personal philosophy is LOVE and Be LOVED.
Billy is a graduate from Georgetown University where he studied Psychology.  He was also the quarterback of the football team for four years.  He had a short stint with the Baltimore Ravens in 1999, which was a great experience and personal achievement.  He continues to credit his athletic experiences with helping him to understand the mind-body connection and the ability to set a life goal with great determination and tenacity. After leaving Baltimore he continued his study of psychology at Seton Hall University where he attained his Masters Degree and Post Masters Degree.
Billy is married to his soul mate and best friend Lia.  They have two sons, two-year-old JD and 5 month old Casey. The family is completed by their Golden Retriever, Grover Ward.

In the spirit of ideas worth spreading, TEDx is a program of local, self-organized events that bring people together to share a TED-like experience. At a TEDx event, TEDTalks video and live speakers combine to spark deep discussion and connection in a small group. These local, self-organized events are branded TEDx, where x = independently organized TED event. The TED Conference provides general guidance for the TEDx program, but individual TEDx events are self-organized.* (*Subject to certain rules and regulations)

Caption Text:
Transcriber: Ilze Garda
Reviewer: Ariana Bleau Lugo Here's the deal: Life is really all about love. I'm not just saying that
because I'm a father of a newborn baby; I'm saying that because
as a teacher and as a therapist I've seen people basically
choose between two things: love or something else. What I've witnessed
and experienced is this: When people choose love, they always choose right. I was asked to speak today
on the topic of illumination, and it made me think about the way
the light inside us all can shine. My favorite way is through our love which can illuminate in our relationships. The most important relationship
that we'll ever have, is the relationship
that we have with ourselves. And next comes the relationships
that we share with one another. As simply as I can put it, we are here, on this very Earth,
to love and to be loved - and love is light. In a second, what I'd like 
to do with you today, is a brief, relaxing, 
guided-imagery exercise, where I'm going to have you
close your eyes and consider three expressions of light
that can return us to love. I'm going to have you close your eyes
and consider three items, and then associate each item
with a person in your life. So, let's get ready. Can I ask you to put
your feet flat on the floor, palms facing up in your lap, and when you're ready, gently allow your upper eyelids
to meet your lower eyelashes. Close your eyes 
and let's everyone take a deep breath. Relax your shoulders. The first item I'd like you
to picture is the sun. Picture the sun in the big, blue sky,
feel the warmth of her rays, and consider how the sun
continues to show up every day, sharing its light and energy
unconditionally, even on a cold February morning. Is there somebody in your life
that reminds you of the sun? Somebody that loves you unconditionally? Picture that person now
and feel their love. The next item I'd like you
to picture is a lighthouse. See the light emanating
from the top of the structure at the ocean's edge
where the sea meets the land, and remember its primary purpose: To help guide sailors and boaters home. Is there somebody in your life
that helps guide you home? To your authentic self? To the truth of who you are? To the person that you're meant to be? To the path that you're meant to be on? Picture that person now and consider the direction
that they're encouraging you to head in. The last item I'd like you
to picture is a disco ball. See the light bouncing off of it, think of the energy in the room
where you might find this unique object, maybe you hear
your favorite song playing. Is there somebody in your life
that reminds you of a disco ball? Somebody that shows up
with the fun, loving energy wherever they are, wherever they go? Picture that person now and consider how they are encouraging
you to live and love. Gently float open your eyes. Today I'd like to share a story with you
about a student of mine. His name was Daniel. I met Daniel the very first year
I was a classroom teacher. I had no experience as a theology teacher
in an all-boys prep school, and somehow this little guy,
this 103-pound wrestler, he became more of a teacher to me
than a student, because he showed me
and everybody in the school building how to shine their love and their light by being an example of how it's done. You see, the same year 
that I met this little guy was the same year
that I was cut from the NFL. Felt like a little bit of my light
had been taken from me when the Baltimore Ravens told me
I can no longer be their quarterback. I had trained with them all summer,
I felt like a kid in Disney, I was playing and competing
with some of my childhood heroes in stadiums
that I had only visited as a fan. Playing in the NFL
was an incredible experience, but at the end of the summer, a week before our first game,
on the last day of cuts, I was released. I had to return home to New Jersey 
to figure out a new career. I had graduated
from Georgetown University with the degree in psychology,
so I guessed I could teach that, but I was hired
at an all-boys prep school to coach football and teach theology. It was kind of like a life course
for the incoming freshmen. Gave me the opportunity to teach the guys the importance of being kind,
caring and thoughtful. It really healed my broken heart. I loved teaching 
as much as I loved playing football. And that's where I met Daniel. He came into my classroom
like a little disco ball. He had an energy and a light about him
that everybody wanted to be around. Daniel connected
with everybody in the school. I used to love watching him
walk the hallways. His smile was reflected back to him
in every corner. Athletes, band guys,
cool guys, smart guys, teachers and coaches, all felt the love of this pint-sized,
103-pound wrestler. People loved Daniel because he was free. He was free to be himself, and most of us know
how difficult that can be. I remember when Daniel
found out it was my birthday during his freshman year. He took it upon himself to create
a homemade birthday card for me. He even taped a Starburst candy
and a pack of Wrigley's gum to the inside. He presented it to me
in front of the class. Daniel was redefining cool, and he made it cool
to be thoughtful, caring and kind, and his classmates loved him for it. It was in this way
that our brotherly bond began. And it was during his sophomore year that Daniel started to campaign
for me to date his older cousin Lia, so that we could officially be family. (Laughter) He even brought her
to a wrestling match one weekend. I was only there
with about one other person, and Daniel had about 15 relatives
cheering him on that night. It was a beautiful night. Then Daniel came into school
the following Monday, and he was mad. He said, "Mr. Ward, you brought
your girlfriend to my wrestling match, when I brought my cousin
to introduce you?" (Laughter) I said, "Wow, Daniel, hold on a second! That girl happens to be my younger sister, (Laughter) and, second of all, I didn't know you were trying
to play matchmaker that night." It felt like a real compliment
to my teachings. My message of love and be loved
was really making an impact. For years, I've been practicing shouting commands
for the NFL football field, but I had been practicing
another message all along. I was never the type of football player
that was overly aggressive or tough. I never yelled at my teammates, and I never yell
at my students in the classroom. Some people say this may make
people walk all over you, but I believe otherwise. An older teacher once told me,
when I first began teaching, that I shouldn't smile in the classroom
until after a few months have gone by. (Laughter) I guess the theory is that the students
would think I was tough, but I love to smile, and I have a different theory. I believe that 
the toughest guy in the room is not the football guy; it's the loving guy. It's the most manly thing
that can ever be accomplished. It's not that difficult to do, but it requires great thought and courage. I loved football because I thought
it was one of the finest team sports. When we're on the field, playing together, relating as teammates, defending each other,
protecting each other, doing a little dance in the end zone
to celebrate the points we score - Football was really about relationships. And so is love. Love is a team sport. A team that we are all a part of. And on this team, Daniel is an all-star. But Daniel never had
the glory of an end zone dance, or even a dance at his junior prom. And that's because his life
extinguished way too early. One night, during Daniel's junior year, in February, he was rolling up the mats
with his wrestling buddies, and he collapsed in pain. Daniel suffered an aortic aneurysm, and he died
early the next morning in hospital. It was tragic. The date was February 7th, 2002. Exactly 12 years ago today. I don't think it's any coincidence
that I'm here today with the opportunity to share Daniel's story with you. Daniel is my lighthouse. When the water is dark and dangerous, the lighthouse can provide
a warm and inviting light, almost as if to say, this way home. Daniel brought me home
literally by bringing me to his home. The night after he died,
I visited his family, along with the number 
of other teachers from our school. We were all greeted
by Daniel's cousin Lia, who thanked us for being there
during such a devastating time. I introduced myself
as Daniel's theology teacher, and she replied, "Oh, you're the one
that Daniel wanted me to marry!" (Laughter) It was kind of like a light went on. I ended up sitting with Lia and her mom, sharing stories of Daniel
and looking at pictures. It was a really difficult time
for us both, but it hard for me not to notice that Lia had the same passion
and energy for life that I saw in Daniel. I wish he could have seen us meet. Riding home that night, I quietly recalled
my last moment with Daniel. He was visiting my class. And like many times before, Daniel would just stroll right in. And because I was sitting behind the desk,
he came over to me, and we're about the same height, and our shoulders bumped
into each other as we talked. I introduced him to the class as the 103-pound wrestler
who was having a great season, and the younger guys
just looked at him in awe. Here was this guy,
smaller than most of them, but he carried so much weight
and loving energy. On his way out 
of the classroom that morning, Daniel turned over his shoulder
in his cool little way and said, "See you around, Mr. Ward." Daniel died early the next morning. Couple of weeks later,
I thought I saw Daniel at school. The student was sitting
with [his] back to me, and it looked like Daniel. And for a moment
I believed that it was him. But soon the student stood,
and it obviously wasn't Daniel. But to me the message was clear. The same love and light that I witnessed 
and experienced in Daniel, could be found in everyone and everything. So I began to look for Daniel, to look for love
in everyone and everything, and at the crucial point in my life,
even in myself. Daniel was right when he said,
"See you around." Because the same love in him
is within us all. Just as I tell my students back at school, there is so much goodness in you, and you are all, each and everyone of you, worthy of love and belonging, just as you are, imperfectly perfect. And once you begin open yourself to love, you will learn to see it everywhere, creating a peace, a freedom and a truth that will shift your overall,
entire experience. Think about it. If I stand right here
and I shift just a little bit, my view changes entirely. The same is true for love. If we can begin to make an effort to love and be loved
without any conditions, we will bring a whole new level of meaning to our relationships
and to our experience. I'm going to ask you
to close your eyes one more time. Picture the sun. Author Anthony de Mello writes: "Has the Sun ever said
to the Earth: you owe me. Look what happens to a love like that.
It lights up the whole sky." Is there somebody in your life
that can use a little unconditional love? Picture that person now. Remember the lighthouse. Remember its primary purpose:
To help guide sailors and boaters home. Is there somebody in your life
that can use a little guidance, a little direction? Picture that person now. And, lastly, picture the disco ball. Daniel was free to be himself because he loved himself unconditionally. We could all reflect 
a little bit of love back home, so that we can dance
like nobody is watching. Is there something in your life
that you've been waiting to do? Gently float open your eyes and smile. Twelve years ago, after Daniel died, I decided to ask his cousin Lia out
for dinner in his honor. We had so much to talk about, and I'm happy to tell you that,
four years after that, I asked Lia to marry me. She continues
to light up my life every day, Lia is my sunshine,
and now we have two sons. Our oldest is almost three,
and his name is John Daniel, whom we affectionately call J.D., and he's our little disco ball. We also have another son,
who is just 12 weeks old now. His name is Casey Christian,
and he's our little lighthouse. When people ask Lia if the boys will play football in the NFL
someday like their daddy did, she says, "Maybe." But our only wish for them
is to truly live a life where they can love and be loved. Thank you very much. (Applause)

Title: C√©line Dion - I Love You (Lyrics)
Description:

Stream/Download:

(Lyrics):
[Intro]
I must be crazy now
Maybe I dream too much
But when I think of you

My baby

Caption Text:
Overwhelmed by
email chaos? The brand new iOS 18
mail update is here, and it's either going to be
your secret weapon or your biggest nightmare. Stick around and find out. I'm Dylan Stewart,
The MacWhisperer. And in this video,
we're going to dive into the brand new iOS
18 mail app, which has some brand new features
like categorization that people are either
loving or hating. Once you know how
to use it, you can decide for yourself. Make sure to stick around
for my MacWhisperer Power Tip, where I deliver
some powerful tools that will change how
you use mail forever. Let's hop on over to the
phone and get started. When you first jump into
the Mail app, you'll usually find yourself
in this view, which is called the Inbox view. But to really understand
how to get around the Mail app, we need to take a
step backwards by clicking our back arrow in the
upper left hand corner here, and starting off
in the Mailboxes view. In the Mailboxes view,
you'll see mailboxes for any email accounts
you've configured . Up at the top, we've got
a section called the Favorites section. The Favorites section
is really helpful because it's completely
customizable. By clicking on the Edit
button in the upper right hand corner, you
can turn off or on any email accounts that
you've got configured. And if you continue to
scroll down, you'll find some really valuable tools
like the VIP section, the Flag section, the
Remind Me section, or even the ability to
turn on your All Trash, All Sent, All Junk, and
all drafts section so that you always have
all your email without hunting around through
the separate accounts. The favorites section
is so powerful that you can add any mailbox
from any account into this section by coming
down to the bottom and choosing add mailbox. Go into whatever email
account that mailbox is located in and just click
on it and click done. Now that mailbox will
show up right at the top of your favorites
section making it really easy for you to get to
that important mailbox. without having to
scroll through all of these other accounts. In fact, if you set up
your favorite section properly, you can usually
turn off all the accounts you see down here by
clicking the arrow to the right and just closing
them up to save space and make it easier to navigate
through your entire mailbox without without
having to scroll around. Take a few moments and set
up your favorite section. Remember, pressing the
edit button will allow you to turn on or off any
accounts, and pressing and holding on the three lines
on the right side will allow you to move sections
up or down to make sure your favorite section
is perfectly configured and gives you everything
you need on one screen. Now let's hop into our
All Inboxes section right here and take a look
at the Inboxes view. The first major change
you'll see in iOS 18's Mail app shows
up in the Inbox view. It's called the Priority
section and the Priority section looks through your
inbox for email messages that maybe you missed but
that are really important. And it brings them right
up to the top to make it easy to Click on them
and address that issue quickly and simply. The priorities are
automatic, so there's nothing you can do to
force something to show up there, but in most cases,
it finds the messages that need your attention
and brings them up so you can find them easily. The next thing you're
going to notice about this new iOS 18 update
is the categories that we see up at the top. We're used to seeing
all of our message in the inbox without any
categorization, but in this new update, Apple
has separated out your inbox into four separate
categories to make sure you can find the most
important messages and not get overwhelmed
by all the junk. The first section is
the primary section, and that's where you'll
find all your email conversations with the
people and the companies that you work with
on a regular basis. Moving one section over
to the right, you'll find the transactions section. In this section, you'll
find any orders, any purchases, any shipments,
any, well, transactions. If it has to do with
money, it's probably going to show up right here. Moving one more
section over to the right, and we end up
in the update section. The update section
highlights communication with companies, giving
you news, newsletters, and even social media
updates all in one place. Moving one over to
the right, We get into our Promotions tab. The Promotions tab is
where you'll find sales, coupons, and all sorts
of promotional emails. One of the things I
like best about the new categorization feature
is that it stacks emails on top of each other. So when I'm in the Update
section and I come down to delete this Tanner
Lee email, it's actually going to delete all
six emails from Tanner Lee at the same time. This is going to make
it so easy for me to quickly get caught
up on my promotion. promotional emails,
my updates and my transactions without
completely losing my mind. Sometimes something
gets put into the wrong category though
but there's a tool that can fix that. This John Smith
should actually be inside of my primary. So if I click on it
here and click on the three dots in the upper
right hand corner, I can categorize the sender
and make sure that he is always categorized
in the primary section. You can move things in
or out of any category by simply going up
to those three dots and recategorizing
that specific sender. As you continue to use
the Mail app, it gets smarter and smarter,
and the categorization gets better and better. Also, if you look over
in the Primary section, you'll see some messages
have a little colored icon to the right side, like
this Experian Alerts here, the Stripe Alert here, or
this Meeting Summary here. These are emails that
the iphone believes to be time sensitive, so
even though normally it would be an update, Or
a transaction, because it's time sensitive,
it automatically shows up in the primary
section to make sure that I don't miss it. Super helpful. But sometimes, you'll
be working on your mail app and you won't want
all of these categories. It's easy to temporarily
turn off the categories by simply tapping on
the active category a second time. So because primary
is currently active, if I tap on it again,
I go into All Mail. And if I was in the
Promotions section and tapped on Promotions
again, I would go into All Mail. When you're in the All
Mail section, you'll see everything from
every category without it being separated. And then it's easy to go
back to the categories by clicking on any one of the
sections and it resets it. This makes it so easy
to have categories. or turn them off if
you don't need to. But if you just hate the
category feature and want it gone forever that's
also really easy to do. By clicking on the three
dots in the upper right corner you can change from
the categories view to the list view which will
put everything back the way it was before iOS 18. Also from that same three
dots you can turn off the show priority if you
don't like that function or it's not accurate. Now let's talk about
some of the other tools that exist inside of
this inboxes view. First off in the lower
left hand corner we've got the mail filter. This is a super helpful
tool that gets overlooked or underutilized. Simply clicking on this
will hide any messages that have already been
read making sure that you only see the unread
messages . If you've got a ton of emails and you
just want to see the new ones this is going to
make it easy to find that. Notice in the bottom
middle where it says filtered by,
it shows unread. If you tap where it says
unread, you can add other options to the filter. You can turn on or off
any emails that you don't want it to search. You can turn on
or off flagged. or attachments, or VIPs,
or only mail sent today. You can make any of
these changes anytime you want and the
filter will immediately reflect those changes. So the next time you
come in and turn on the filter, it'll eliminate
anything that doesn't match those requirements. If you are going to change
your standard filter, I recommend coming back
and changing it to unread when you're done playing
around, because between you and I, that's the best
filter feature there is. Also, in the upper right
hand corner, you've got a Select button. The Select button can
allow you to easily select multiple messages, and
using the buttons down at the bottom, you can
click the Mark button to mark it as junk, mark
it as read, or flag it. You can click the move
button to move those messages into any
folder in any one of your email accounts. Or, you can just trash
it by clicking the trash button on the
bottom right corner. A little pro tip for
you when you're using the select function. If you put your finger
down on the circle on the left and just roll
downwards, you can select a large number of messages
without having to click them one at a time. This is really helpful
if you're in the update section or the promotion
section and you just want to clean house and get
rid of all of that junk that's been holding you
back since, well, forever. Next, let's talk about
the swiping tools that we can use from this view. We can swipe from either
the left side or the right side of any email
message, and depending on which way we swipe,
there's lots of options. Swiping from the
left to the right, we have two options. The Unread option,
which can mark a message as read or unread. And the Remind Me option. The Remind Me option will
set a reminder that will bring this email up to the
top of your inbox at the time that you specified
so that you can remember to reply to it or add
additional information in. Swiping from the right
side to the left side, we have three options. The trash option, the
option to flag a message. Flagging is really,
really helpful because it can allow you to
easily find specific kinds of messages. I use all kinds
of different flags in my mail. For example, one of my
flags tracks orders that have not yet arrived. One of them tracks bills. One of them tracks
travel itineraries. And one of them tracks
all the important messages that I want to make sure
I respond to quickly. And then we've also got
the More button here. The More button does
the exact same function as the Reply button,
which we'll talk about in just a moment. Another little pro
tip for you here. If you are doing a partial
swipe, you will then have to click the next button. But if you do a complete
swipe all the way from the left side to the
right side like this, it will automatically
perform the action. So from the left side
to the right side, it will turn this message
from unread to read. to read without my
having to stop and click in the middle. And again, if you do
a partial swipe from the right side, you'll
then have to click the separate options. But if you do a full
swipe from the right side to the left side, it
will immediately delete that message with one
clean, simple gesture. Now, let's step into the
message view by clicking on one of our emails. Once we're inside
of the message view, there's several
options we can use. Down in the lower left
hand corner, clicking the trash icon will
delete this message. Clicking the folder
icon will move this message into one of
our email folders. You'll notice here it
gives a suggestion at the bottom suggesting that
it should move it to sent messages, but if you click
up above where it says move message, you can
choose any folder from any account right from here. To the right of
that, we've got the Reply button. Clicking the Reply button
opens up a host of tools. You'll see Reply, Reply
All, Forward, and Trash. But if you continue
scrolling down, you'll find a section where you
can create a reminder, or set yourself a flag. Remember, you can set
flags in a number of different colors, allowing
you to categorize one color as one type of
email, and another color as something else, so
you can quickly locate things like your orders,
or your itineraries. Continuing to scroll
down, you've got a ton of other options, including
the Categorize Sender option, in case you need
to train this sender into a different category. But don't overlook
the fact that you can print your email from
right here as well. Clicking on this print
button will open up a screen allowing you to
connect to any wireless printers and allowing you
to print this message out right from your phone. In addition to that,
in the upper right hand corner we've got the
ability to click these arrows to go down to the
next message or up to the previous message. This can make it really
easy to look through a lot of your emails without
going back and forth to different screens. You can also click up at
the top right here to get more information about who
sent the message and if there were any CCs, BCCs,
or other information. Now let's create a
brand new email message by clicking on the
new email icon in the bottom right corner. Notice that the new
message icon is in the bottom right
corner on every one of the mail screens. So whether you're
inside of a message. Inside of your inbox or
in your mailbox view, you can always easily
start a new message. Let's go ahead
and click it. From the new message
view up at the top we can address our email. You can do this by typing
a couple of letters and it will look inside
of your address book. But if you don't know
who you want to send it to or you want to send
it to an entire group, click the plus button
on the right side which will open up your whole
address book allowing you access to any of
your address book groups or any of the people
in your address book. Simply clicking
on anyone's name will add them right
into this email. Down below that we've got
the CC and BCC section. Clicking right here will
open up this section where you can carbon
copy or blind carbon copy anyone from this email. And down below we've
got the From section. If you've got multiple
email accounts on your phone, this is where you
can come and click on the email address to choose
a different email to send this message from. It will default to
whatever your default email account is. And if you're not sure
what that is, head over to Settings, Go down to
the bottom where it says apps and open up mail
and check and see what your default account is. The default account should
be set to whichever email address you use the most. Moving down below
that we've got our subject section where
